  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The highest and lowest price levels formed during the Asian, London, and New York trading sessions. These levels act as intraday liquidity pools, used to frame the daily narrative, draw liquidity, or identify potential reversal points.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify the start and end times of the specific trading session (e.g., Asian, London, New York).",
    "Mark the highest price of the Asian session (approx. 20:00–00:00 EST) as Asia high.",
    "Mark the lowest price of the Asian session as Asia low.",
    "Mark the highest price of the London session (approx. 02:00–05:00 EST) as London high.",
    "Mark the lowest price of the London session as London low.",
    "Mark the highest price of the New York session (approx. 08:30–11:00 EST) as New York high.",
    "Mark the lowest price of the New York session as New York low.",
    "Draw horizontal lines on the chart at these price levels for future reference."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Session highs and lows serve as liquidity targets and reversal zones. Price often sweeps one session's level before moving to another, providing draw-on-liquidity objectives. They help frame intraday bias and entry areas, such as looking for reactions at London high/low before targeting Asia high/low. Unbroken levels across multiple sessions can form equal highs/lows, increasing their significance as support/resistance.",
